/* Practice challenges — RN System Design: staff-level scenarios */
(function () {
  var reg = window.PREP_SITE.registerChallenge;

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-offline-sync', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design the offline-first data layer for a field-service RN app: technicians create and edit work orders with no connectivity for hours at a time, then sync when back online. How do you handle local persistence, queued mutations, conflict resolution, and consistency guarantees?',
    answer: {
      approach: `Before designing anything, pin down: can two technicians edit the <em>same</em> record concurrently, or is each record effectively single-owner while offline? How long can a device stay offline (minutes vs a full shift)? Is the server the ultimate source of truth, and are there audit/compliance requirements on edit history? Is the data shape simple field updates, or does it include ordered events (status transitions, notes) that might merge more naturally than raw field overwrites? The conflict-resolution design changes completely depending on these answers — treating it as "just add a sync button" is the first red flag.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Distinguishes a <strong>local cache</strong> (read replica of server state) from an <strong>offline write queue</strong> (mutation log awaiting flush) — these are different data structures with different lifecycles, not one blob.</li><li>Picks a persistence layer sized to the problem (SQLite/WatermelonDB/op-sqlite for structured, queryable, potentially large local data) rather than defaulting to AsyncStorage for anything beyond trivial key-value state.</li><li>Addresses <strong>idempotency</strong> explicitly: a mutation retried after a flaky network drop must not double-apply server-side.</li><li>Names an actual conflict-resolution policy (LWW by timestamp, event-sourced merge, or explicit user-facing merge UI) tied to the product's real semantics, not "we'll diff the JSON."</li><li>Considers what happens if the app crashes or the device reboots mid-sync — is the queue durable and resumable, or does a crash silently lose queued work?</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Local store:</strong> SQLite (via WatermelonDB or a lighter-weight driver) as the on-device source of truth for work-order records, not just a cache — the app reads/writes locally first, always. <strong>Write queue:</strong> every local mutation gets a client-generated UUID and is appended to a durable outbox table, independent of the record table itself, so the queue survives app kill/reboot. A background sync engine flushes the outbox when <code>NetInfo</code> reports connectivity, with exponential backoff on failure. <strong>Idempotency:</strong> the client-generated mutation UUID is sent as an idempotency key; the server stores a dedupe table keyed on it, so a retried request (ack lost, not the mutation) returns the original result instead of executing twice. <strong>Conflict resolution:</strong> model discrete changes as an append-only <em>event log</em> where possible (<code>status_changed</code>, <code>note_added</code>) rather than mutable field overwrites — most concurrent edits from two offline technicians commute naturally (two different notes just both land). For fields that genuinely conflict (the same status field set to two different values while both offline), use server-authoritative last-write-wins by validated server timestamp, with the losing client shown an explicit "your change was overridden" notice rather than silently dropped. <strong>UI:</strong> optimistic updates applied immediately against the local store, with a per-record sync-status indicator (synced / pending / conflict) so users aren't misled about durability. <strong>Testing:</strong> chaos-test with airplane-mode toggling and forced app kill mid-queue to verify the outbox is genuinely durable, not just "usually fine in the happy path."
<pre><code class="language-js">// Outbox entry shape — independent of the record itself
{ id: 'a1b2c3', entity: 'workOrder', entityId: 'wo_42',
  op: 'update', patch: { status: 'completed' },
  createdAt: 1751700000000, attempts: 0 }
</code></pre>`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'How do you handle a conflict where two technicians edited the same work order while both offline?', a: 'Model discrete state transitions as immutable, appended events rather than overwriting a mutable object, so most concurrent edits commute naturally. For the subset of fields that genuinely conflict (the same field set to two different values), apply a resolution policy — typically last-write-wins by server-authoritative timestamp with the losing client explicitly notified its change was overridden, or a manual merge UI for high-value data where silently picking a winner is unacceptable.' },
        { q: 'What happens if a mutation is retried after the server actually processed it but the acknowledgment was lost on the way back?', a: 'The client-generated mutation UUID doubles as an idempotency key; the server keeps a dedupe table keyed on it, so a retried request with the same key is a no-op that returns the original result rather than re-executing the mutation a second time.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-chat-messaging', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design the client architecture for a 1:1 and group chat feature at scale (10k+ concurrent users): realtime delivery, infinite-scroll history pagination, optimistic send with retry, and read receipts.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Clarify the transport expectations first: is a persistent WebSocket acceptable, or does the app need a push-notification fallback for backgrounded/killed states? Is strict message ordering required, or is eventual, mostly-ordered delivery fine? Are attachments/media in scope, and is end-to-end encryption a requirement (changes what the client is allowed to cache/search)? What's the largest expected group size — a 5-person DM group and a 5,000-person broadcast channel need different pagination and fan-out assumptions.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Separates <strong>transport</strong> (socket connect/reconnect) from <strong>state management</strong> (message store) — a reconnect shouldn't force re-deriving the entire message list from scratch.</li><li>Reconciles optimistic sends via a stable client-generated ID matched against the server-assigned ID, not array-index or timestamp guessing.</li><li>Uses <strong>cursor-based</strong> pagination (anchored to a message ID/sequence number) for history, not offset-based paging, which breaks under concurrent inserts.</li><li>Picks a recycling list (FlashList v2) for the message view using the current chat-UI pattern — <code>maintainVisibleContentPosition</code> plus <code>startRenderingFromBottom: true</code>, not the deprecated <code>inverted</code> prop — and actively avoids re-render storms from high-frequency socket events (typing indicators, read receipts).</li><li>Addresses the reconnect/gap-fill problem: messages that arrived while the app was backgrounded or the socket was disconnected.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Transport:</strong> a WebSocket connection (raw WS or socket.io) with automatic reconnect and exponential backoff; REST endpoints handle bulk history fetch and any large payload work sockets are a poor fit for. <strong>Local store:</strong> messages normalized by chat ID in a client store (Zustand/Redux), persisted to SQLite/MMKV for offline history access. <strong>Rendering:</strong> FlashList v2 keyed by stable message ID, bottom-anchored via <code>maintainVisibleContentPosition</code> combined with <code>startRenderingFromBottom: true</code> — FlashList v2 deprecated the <code>inverted</code> prop for chat-style UIs in favor of this pattern — with memoized row components so a single incoming socket event doesn't re-render the whole visible list. Note: this newer pattern has known scroll-position regressions with backfilled/paginated history, so validate it explicitly against your own pagination flow before committing to it. <strong>Optimistic send:</strong> construct a message with a client-generated UUID and status <code>'sending'</code>, append immediately, dispatch via the socket/HTTP; on ack, reconcile the temp ID to the server-assigned ID <em>in place</em> (swap, don't append a duplicate); on failure, mark <code>'failed'</code> with an explicit retry affordance rather than silently dropping it. <strong>Pagination:</strong> cursor = oldest visible message's ID/timestamp, fetched via REST on scroll-to-top, not via the socket (sockets are for realtime push, not bulk backfill). <strong>Read receipts:</strong> debounce and batch read-receipt calls (e.g., "furthest message read" per chat every few seconds) instead of firing one API call per message viewed. <strong>Reconnect/gap-fill:</strong> the client persists the last-acknowledged sequence number per chat; on reconnect, it requests "everything since sequence N" from the server rather than assuming the socket delivered everything that happened while disconnected.
<pre><code class="language-js">// Optimistic message reconciliation
function onServerAck(tempId, serverMsg) {
  setMessages(prev => prev.map(m =>
    m.clientId === tempId ? { ...serverMsg, clientId: tempId, status: 'sent' } : m));
}
</code></pre>`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'How do you avoid a re-render storm when the socket delivers 50 messages at once during a channel history backfill?', a: 'Batch incoming messages and coalesce them into a single state update per animation-frame/microtask boundary, instead of dispatching a state update per individual message — the list should re-render once for the batch, not fifty times.' },
        { q: 'How do you keep message ordering correct when a client-side optimistic timestamp differs from the server-assigned one?', a: 'Sort by the server-assigned sequence number/timestamp once a message is acknowledged; while a message is still pending, position it at the local tail by insertion order, and only re-sort on reconciliation rather than on every render.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-image-feed-low-end', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design a large, image-heavy social feed (Instagram-like) that must scroll at a smooth frame rate on low-end Android devices (2-3GB RAM, mid/low-tier SoCs).',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask: are image aspect ratios known ahead of render (from API metadata) or discovered on load — this determines whether layout jank from reflow is avoidable? Is video mixed into the feed (autoplay adds its own cost budget)? Is this infinite-scroll or paginated? What's the actual target device profile — "low-end Android" spans a wide range, and the design should target the worst realistic device, not the median.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Picks a recycling list (FlashList v2) over <code>FlatList</code> and can explain the mechanism (cell recycling vs mount/unmount per scroll), not just "it's faster."</li><li>Addresses image sizing explicitly: requesting server-resized images matching render dimensions, not shipping full-resolution originals into a small feed cell.</li><li>Reserves layout space using known aspect-ratio metadata to prevent reflow/jank when images load asynchronously.</li><li>Bounds memory: an LRU-style image cache with eviction, not an unbounded cache that grows until the OS kills the app.</li><li>Keeps row components memoized and avoids inline function/object props that defeat memoization on every scroll-triggered re-render.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>List:</strong> FlashList v2 for windowed cell recycling — it reuses existing native view instances instead of FlatList's mount/unmount-per-scroll model, which is the single biggest lever on constrained hardware at feed scale. <strong>Images:</strong> use an image component with a built-in decode/cache pipeline (expo-image or an equivalent), request CDN-resized images matching the actual render width (never full-resolution originals), and decode a blurhash/thumbhash placeholder synchronously for instant paint before the real image arrives. <strong>Layout stability:</strong> the API returns image aspect ratio alongside the URL, so the cell reserves its final height before the image loads — no reflow jank when the image resolves. <strong>Memory bounds:</strong> a bounded LRU image cache that evicts the least-recently-visible images, plus a limited prefetch distance (a few screens ahead, not the whole remaining feed) to cap peak memory. <strong>Render cost:</strong> row components wrapped in <code>React.memo</code> with stable, precomputed props (hoisted callbacks via <code>useCallback</code>, no inline arrow functions/object literals created fresh per render) so a parent re-render doesn't cascade into re-rendering every visible cell. <strong>Scroll-time work:</strong> defer non-critical work (analytics pings, prefetch kicks) via <code>InteractionManager</code> so it doesn't compete with scroll for JS-thread time; anything visually reactive to scroll offset (parallax headers, fade effects) runs via a Reanimated worklet on the UI thread, not a JS-thread scroll listener. <strong>Device-aware degrade:</strong> on detected low memory-class devices, request a lower image-quality tier from the CDN outright rather than applying the same asset budget everywhere.`,
      followups: [
        { q: "What's the risk of loading full-resolution images to save \"one less network request\"?", a: 'Decode cost and memory footprint per cell scale with the actual pixel dimensions delivered, not the display size — oversized images cause GC pressure and raise OOM-kill risk on low-RAM devices, and the decode itself can drop frames mid-scroll. Always request server-resized images matching render dimensions.' },
        { q: 'Why prefer FlashList v2 over FlatList here specifically?', a: "FlashList recycles cell view instances instead of FlatList's mount/unmount-on-scroll approach, cutting both JS reconciliation and native view churn dramatically — exactly the cost that's most punishing on low-end hardware. FlashList v2 also removed the need to hand-tune estimatedItemSize via automatic sizing, removing a common source of misconfigured jank." }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-ota-release', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design the release and OTA update strategy for a production RN app on EAS: staged rollout, fast rollback, and safely handling native/JS version skew — a JS update must never be served to a native binary it is incompatible with.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Confirm the toolchain (bare RN vs Expo/EAS) since the answer is materially different outside the Expo ecosystem. Ask about release cadence and native-module churn — an app that rarely touches native code can lean harder on OTA; one with frequent native changes needs the binary-release path to be equally well-oiled. Ask what risk appetite exists for staged rollout percentages and what monitoring already exists to detect a bad rollout quickly.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Knows CodePush is deprecated and EAS Update is the current OTA mechanism for Expo/EAS-based RN apps.</li><li>Understands OTA can only ship JS/asset changes — never native code — and explains the mechanism that structurally prevents a JS update reaching an incompatible binary (runtime-version/fingerprint matching), rather than relying on developer discipline.</li><li>Designs an actual staged rollout (percentage-based) with monitoring gates before ramping to 100%, plus a rollback path measured in minutes, not a new build/review cycle.</li><li>Recognizes that native-module or config changes are structurally not OTA-eligible and require a real store release, and designs a minimum-supported-version gate for binaries too old to safely receive newer OTA updates at all.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Build vs update split:</strong> EAS Build produces native binaries; EAS Update delivers JS/asset OTA updates into already-installed binaries. <strong>Skew prevention:</strong> every native build is stamped with a runtime version (an explicit policy or derived from native fingerprint); EAS Update only ever serves an update whose runtime version matches the installed binary's — this makes JS/native skew structurally impossible rather than a discipline problem, since an incompatible update is simply never delivered to that binary. <strong>Channels:</strong> map <code>production</code>/<code>staging</code>/<code>preview</code> EAS Update channels to matching build profiles, each scoped to a runtime-version branch. <strong>Staged rollout:</strong> publish a JS update to a channel with a rollout percentage (e.g. 10%), watch crash-free-session rate and critical-error dashboards scoped to that update group specifically, then ramp in stages (25% → 50% → 100%) only once metrics hold. <strong>Rollback:</strong> reverting is re-pointing the channel's active update group back to the previous one — a metadata change, not a rebuild, so it's near-instant compared to waiting on store review. <strong>Native changes:</strong> anything touching native modules/permissions/config is not OTA-eligible by construction (the runtime-version gate enforces this automatically) and must go through a normal binary build + store review. <strong>Old-binary protection:</strong> a remotely-configured minimum-supported-version check nudges/hard-blocks binaries too old to safely keep receiving current OTA updates, forcing a store update instead of silently degrading.`,
      followups: [
        { q: "Why can't you ship a new native module via OTA to skip an App Store review cycle?", a: "OTA only re-delivers the JS bundle and assets into the existing installed binary/runtime — it can't add compiled native code that doesn't already exist on the device. Attempting this would both violate App Store policy (using OTA to change app behavior in ways that require native review) and crash at runtime, since the JS would reference a native module the installed binary was never compiled with." },
        { q: 'How do you detect a bad OTA rollout fast enough for it to matter?', a: "Pair the staged rollout percentage with real-time crash-free-session and critical-error-rate monitoring scoped specifically to that update group's ID, with alert thresholds tighter than the normal release cadence — so a 10% canary spiking crashes trips an alert and blocks the ramp to 100% before most users are affected." }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-deep-linking-nav', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design deep-linking and navigation-state restoration for a large RN app on React Navigation v7: a push notification, universal link, or app relaunch must land the user on the exact right screen with a correct back-stack, including for authenticated-only destinations.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask which link sources are in scope (universal/app links, custom scheme, push notification payloads, QR codes) since cold-start handling differs by source. Ask whether some deep-link destinations require auth and what should happen if the user isn't logged in yet when the link arrives. Ask whether restoration needs to survive a full app kill, not just backgrounding, since that changes the persistence requirement substantially.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Uses React Navigation's declarative <code>linking</code> config to map URL patterns to screens/params in one place, instead of imperative navigation calls scattered across app-boot code that race against navigator readiness.</li><li>Explicitly handles the auth-gated deep link problem: a link to a protected screen arriving before auth state resolves must be buffered and replayed, not silently dropped.</li><li>Distinguishes cold-start deep links (<code>Linking.getInitialURL()</code>) from already-running deep links (the runtime event listener) and doesn't just handle one.</li><li>Synthesizes a sensible parent back-stack for a deep link into a nested screen, rather than leaving a dead-end screen with no meaningful back behavior.</li><li>Persists navigation state for restoration across an app kill, but version-gates it against app-schema changes so a stale persisted state can't crash a post-update restore.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Linking config:</strong> a single declarative <code>linking</code> object maps URL path patterns to screen/param shapes across all navigators, consumed uniformly by both the cold-start initial URL and the runtime <code>Linking</code> listener — one source of truth instead of duplicated imperative logic in two places. <strong>Auth gating:</strong> if a deep link targets a protected screen and auth state isn't yet resolved, buffer the pending route in memory/a small store; once auth resolves, either navigate immediately (already authenticated) or route to login and replay the buffered destination afterward (not authenticated) — only drop it if it's genuinely invalid or expired, never silently. <strong>Back-stack synthesis:</strong> use the linking config / <code>getStateFromPath</code> to construct the natural parent chain for a deep destination (e.g. linking into a chat thread pushes the chat list, then the thread, so hardware/gesture back behaves sensibly) rather than mounting only the target screen in isolation. <strong>State restoration:</strong> persist navigation state via React Navigation's <code>onStateChange</code> + MMKV/AsyncStorage, restored through <code>initialState</code> on relaunch — but stamp the persisted blob with an app/schema version and compare it at restore time; on mismatch (a route was renamed/removed since the last session), discard the persisted state and boot to a clean initial route instead of attempting to hydrate a tree referencing routes that no longer exist.
<pre><code class="language-js">const linking = {
  prefixes: ['myapp://', 'https://app.example.com'],
  config: { screens: { Chats: 'chats', Thread: 'chats/:threadId' } },
};
</code></pre>`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'What happens when a push notification deep-links to a screen requiring data fetched from the network (e.g. an order ID that needs validating)?', a: "Navigate to the destination screen immediately, driven by the param (order ID), and show a loading state inside that screen while the fetch resolves — don't block the navigation transaction itself on the network round-trip. If the fetch fails or the ID is invalid, render an error/not-found state in place rather than failing the navigation." },
        { q: 'How do you prevent stale persisted navigation state from crashing the app after a refactor removes a screen?', a: 'Version-stamp the persisted state blob with a schema/build identifier and compare it against the current app version at restore time; on a mismatch, discard the persisted state entirely and boot to the default initial route instead of trying to hydrate a state tree that references routes that no longer exist.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-design-system', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design a shared component/design-system library consumed by 5+ RN app teams in a monorepo: theming, versioning, cross-platform consistency, and safe rollout of breaking changes.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask what design tokens actually come from (a Figma-tokens pipeline vs hand-authored) since that determines whether tokens need automated sync tooling. Ask whether all consumer teams track the same RN version or a spread, since that constrains how aggressively the library can adopt new-arch-only features. Ask whether visual regression testing exists anywhere in the org already, and what release cadence consumer teams expect.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Separates platform-agnostic <strong>design tokens</strong> (colors, spacing, typography as data) from <strong>component implementation</strong>, so tokens can also drive a web/marketing surface consistently.</li><li>Proposes real semver discipline with a deprecation window for breaking prop/behavior changes, not "just bump the version and tell people."</li><li>Builds theming on a Context-based provider consumed by all components, not scattered hardcoded colors or ad hoc <code>Platform.select</code> color branches.</li><li>Includes visual regression testing (snapshot-based) in the release pipeline to catch unintended diffs before publish.</li><li>Acknowledges the organizational reality: a design-system team can't unilaterally break five consumer apps — needs a rollout contract (canary tag, migration codemods, a maximum-version-lag policy).</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Layered structure:</strong> (1) a pure design-token package (colors, spacing scale, typography scale, radii) generated from Figma tokens via a transform pipeline (e.g. Style Dictionary), consumable by RN components and any RN-Web/marketing surface alike; (2) primitive components (Button, Text, Input) built only from tokens plus a <code>ThemeProvider</code> exposing light/dark and per-tenant overrides; (3) composite/pattern components (Card, ListItem) composed from primitives. <strong>Versioning:</strong> strict semver — breaking prop/behavior changes bump major, ship with a deprecation shim (old prop still works but console-warns) for at least one release cycle, and a migration codemod for anything non-trivial; each consumer team pins a version range and follows a scheduled upgrade cadence rather than floating on latest. <strong>Safety net:</strong> component-level visual snapshot testing (Storybook + a screenshot-diff step) in CI blocks publishing a version with unintended visual diffs; a canary/beta npm dist-tag is consumed by one pilot team before promoting to the stable tag the other four teams pull from. <strong>Cross-platform:</strong> platform-specific style differences live inside the component itself (<code>Platform.select</code>) rather than leaking platform conditionals into every consumer app's call sites.`,
      followups: [
        { q: "A consumer team needs a one-off visual variant the system doesn't support — add it to the shared library, or let them fork locally?", a: "Weigh reusability (would a second team plausibly need this within a quarter or two) against system bloat. A genuine one-off should be composed from existing primitives in the consumer's own code (slot-based composition, a style-override escape hatch) rather than growing the shared library's surface for a single caller — only promote it into the library once a second, independent team needs the same thing." },
        { q: 'How do you stop five teams from silently drifting onto incompatible design-system versions?', a: 'Enforce a maximum supported version lag via a CI/dependency-audit check that fails builds pinned more than N majors behind, paired with published migration guides and codemods per major version release so upgrading is a routine, low-friction task rather than a dreaded, deferred one.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-analytics-crash', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design the analytics event pipeline and crash-reporting setup for a production RN app: event taxonomy, offline batching, PII handling, and getting actionable native + JS crash symbolication.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask which vendors are already committed to (Segment/Amplitude/Firebase, Sentry/Bugsnag) since the design should fit real constraints, not a greenfield ideal. Ask what compliance regime applies (GDPR and similar) since that dictates how aggressively PII must be scrubbed before events leave the device. Ask whether crashes are currently more of a JS-side or native-side problem, and whether anyone currently uploads source maps/symbol files at all.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Designs a typed event-taxonomy layer instead of accepting ad hoc <code>track('button_clicked')</code> calls with inconsistent, drifting prop shapes across the codebase.</li><li>Handles offline batching explicitly (local queue, capped size, connectivity-aware flush) instead of silently dropping events when offline.</li><li>Distinguishes JS-thread errors from native crashes, and specifically calls out that Hermes bytecode crash traces are useless without uploaded source maps — same idea for native dSYMs/ProGuard mappings.</li><li>Puts PII redaction at the point of event <em>construction</em> on-device, not "trust the vendor to scrub it downstream."</li><li>Considers sampling for high-volume, low-value events to control ingestion cost without starving conversion-critical events.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Taxonomy:</strong> define a typed event contract (a TS union of event name → payload shape) and force all instrumentation through a single <code>track(event)</code> wrapper, enforced by a lint rule against calling vendor SDKs directly — this is what actually prevents the taxonomy from drifting into inconsistent ad hoc names/props over time. <strong>Transport:</strong> events buffer into a local MMKV-backed queue, flushed in batches (every N events or T seconds) gated by <code>NetInfo</code> connectivity, with a capped queue size and oldest-event eviction so offline usage neither silently loses events nor grows storage unbounded. <strong>PII:</strong> strip/redact sensitive fields (tokens, emails, precise location) at the point the event object is constructed, backed by a documented allowlist of permitted fields reviewed at PR time — not relying on the analytics vendor to scrub anything after the fact. <strong>Crash reporting:</strong> wire a crash SDK (e.g. Sentry) for both JS (global error handler, an ErrorBoundary, and an unhandled-promise-rejection handler) and native crash capture. Critically, upload Hermes bytecode source maps and native debug symbols (iOS dSYMs, Android ProGuard/R8 mapping + native <code>.so</code> symbols) as a <em>mandatory, CI-verified</em> step per release — without it, crash traces resolve to opaque bytecode offsets or obfuscated symbol names instead of real file/line. <strong>Sampling:</strong> apply sampling to extremely high-volume, low-analytical-value events (scroll pings) while keeping conversion/critical-funnel events unsampled.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'A stakeholder reports crashes spiked after the last release, but the crash dashboard shows minified/garbled stack traces — what happened and what do you fix?', a: "That release's Hermes source maps (and/or native symbol files) weren't uploaded, so the crash reporter can't map bytecode offsets or obfuscated symbols back to source. Fix: make source-map/dSYM/mapping-file upload a mandatory, verified CI step that fails the release job on upload failure, and backfill the current release's maps if they're still recoverable." },
        { q: 'How do you keep analytics call sites from drifting out of sync with what the data team actually expects downstream?', a: 'A single typed event-contract layer the whole app is forced through (compile-time checked event names and payload shapes) paired with a lightweight review step whenever an event is added or changed — not trusting scattered, hand-written track() calls to stay consistent by convention.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-auth-session', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design authentication/session management for an RN app: access + refresh token storage, silent refresh, biometric re-auth, multi-device session handling, and secure storage on both iOS and Android.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask about the auth protocol in use (OAuth2/OIDC vs a custom scheme) and expected token lifetimes. Ask whether biometric unlock is a hard product requirement or nice-to-have, and whether concurrent multi-device sessions are expected to be allowed, limited, or exclusive. Ask how sensitive the data is overall (a banking-grade app has a materially different bar than a casual social app) since that changes how paranoid the token-theft handling needs to be.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Never stores tokens in AsyncStorage/plain MMKV — uses the platform secure-storage primitive (Keychain on iOS, Keystore-backed encrypted storage on Android) via a library like react-native-keychain or expo-secure-store.</li><li>Designs a <strong>single-flight</strong> token refresh so N concurrent 401s trigger exactly one refresh call, not a refresh storm that races itself under token rotation.</li><li>Treats biometric re-auth as a local app-lock gate on an already-valid session, not confuses it with the actual server authentication mechanism.</li><li>Addresses refresh-token rotation and theft detection: an already-used, rotated-away refresh token being presented again is a signal, not a shrug.</li><li>Designs real logout as both local secure-storage wipe <em>and</em> server-side token revocation — not just a client-side clear.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Storage:</strong> access token kept in memory (short-lived, cheaply re-derived); refresh token persisted in the platform secure-enclave-backed store (Keychain / Android Keystore-backed storage via react-native-keychain or expo-secure-store) — never AsyncStorage or plaintext MMKV. <strong>Silent refresh:</strong> an HTTP interceptor catches 401s and implements single-flight refresh — a shared in-flight promise so concurrent failing requests trigger exactly one refresh call, with all queued requests replaying against the new access token once it resolves, avoiding a refresh storm that would otherwise race against itself. <strong>Rotation and theft signal:</strong> each refresh call returns a new refresh token and invalidates the previous one server-side; if an already-rotated-away refresh token is ever presented again, treat it as a possible-theft signal and force a full re-login across all of that user's sessions rather than silently honoring it. <strong>Biometric re-auth:</strong> Face ID/Touch ID (via a Keychain-integrated biometric gate) protects <em>local access</em> to the still-valid session — e.g. re-confirming presence after the app has been backgrounded past a timeout — it does not replace or duplicate server auth. <strong>Multi-device:</strong> the server tracks active sessions per device/refresh-token family; a "log out other devices" action revokes server-side, and orphaned sessions get force-logged-out on next token use or app foreground. <strong>Logout:</strong> clears secure storage locally <em>and</em> revokes the token server-side — a client-only wipe leaves a captured token valid until its natural expiry.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'Why keep the access token only in memory rather than persisting it anywhere?', a: "Access tokens are short-lived and cheaply re-derived from the refresh token, so persisting them adds attack surface (a device dump could yield a still-valid access token) for little benefit. The credential actually worth hardened, persistent storage is the longer-lived refresh token, which lives in the secure-enclave-backed store instead." },
        { q: "What breaks if you skip single-flight refresh?", a: "Multiple concurrent API calls each independently hit a 401 and each fire their own refresh request. Under refresh-token rotation, only the first succeeds and invalidates the token the others are about to present, so the rest fail — potentially forcing an unnecessary full logout even though the session was genuinely still valid." }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-large-list-search', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design a large-list + search/filter screen — e.g. a searchable catalog of 50k+ products or contacts — with instant-feeling search-as-you-type, combinable filters, and smooth scrolling.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask whether search runs against a server API or must work fully offline against on-device data, since a client-only 50k-item dataset needs a fundamentally different search structure than a thin client hitting a server search endpoint. Ask the acceptable latency budget for results, whether filters are combinable facets or mutually exclusive, and whether the full dataset is ever resident on-device at once.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Never proposes re-filtering the full in-memory dataset with a linear <code>.filter()</code> on every keystroke — recognizes that's O(n) JS-thread work per character and will drop frames at this scale.</li><li>Debounces input dispatch and, for server search, cancels the previous in-flight request on each new keystroke rather than letting stale requests pile up.</li><li>For offline/client-side search, proposes an actual index (trie/inverted index, or SQLite FTS) built once, not scanned per keystroke.</li><li>Uses a recycling list (FlashList v2) for results with stable keys, and doesn't remount the whole list tree on every keystroke.</li><li>Explicitly handles out-of-order responses — a slow, earlier request resolving after a faster, later one must not clobber the fresher result.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `For a 50k+ item catalog, prefer <strong>server-side search</strong>: debounce query dispatch (roughly 250-300ms after the last keystroke), cancel the previous in-flight request via <code>AbortController</code> on each new keystroke, and tag every dispatched request with a monotonically increasing sequence number so a late-arriving stale response is discarded even if it technically resolves after a newer one — this specifically guards against an older-but-slower response overwriting a newer, faster result. If genuine offline search is required, build an index once up front (a trie/inverted index over searchable fields, or hand the problem to SQLite FTS5 or a dedicated on-device search library) rather than linear-scanning the raw array per keystroke — an O(n) filter over 50k items per typed character is exactly the JS-thread work that blocks input responsiveness. <strong>Rendering:</strong> results render in FlashList v2 with a stable <code>keyExtractor</code> and memoized rows; filters/facets compose as additional query params (server) or additional index predicates (client) alongside the text query rather than running as an independent second pass. <strong>UX:</strong> keep the previous results visible (not flashed to empty) while a new query resolves, show a lightweight non-blocking loading indicator, and render an explicit empty state only once a request genuinely completes with zero results.
<pre><code class="language-js">let seq = 0;
async function onSearchChange(query) {
  const mySeq = ++seq;
  const results = await searchApi(query, { signal: controller.signal });
  if (mySeq !== seq) return; // a newer request already superseded this one
  setResults(results);
}
</code></pre>`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'Why debounce instead of throttle for a search input?', a: "Debounce waits for a pause in typing before firing, matching the actual user intent of \"I've stopped typing, show me results now,\" and minimizes wasted requests for intermediate, not-yet-final query strings. Throttle would fire at fixed intervals mid-typing regardless of whether the user is still composing their query." },
        { q: 'How do you handle out-of-order search responses?', a: "Attach a monotonically increasing sequence number (or use AbortController) to every dispatched search request; when a response arrives, compare it to the latest dispatched sequence number and discard it if it's not current — preventing a slow, earlier response from clobbering a faster, more recent result." }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-theming-a11y', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'senior', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'Design the theming system (light/dark, plus possible per-tenant brand themes) and the accessibility strategy for an RN app used by a broad user base, including screen-reader and low-vision users.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask whether theme switching is purely system-driven or must support an explicit in-app user toggle that persists. Ask if white-labeling/per-tenant branding is in scope, since that adds a dimension beyond light/dark. Ask what accessibility conformance level is targeted (WCAG AA is the common baseline) and whether this is a greenfield build or a retrofit onto components that already hardcode colors.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Builds theming on a token-based Context provider with runtime switching, not scattered <code>Platform.OS === ... ? colorA : colorB</code> branches or a static one-time system-color-scheme read.</li><li>Goes beyond "add accessibilityLabel" — addresses dynamic type/font scaling, verified color contrast per theme, correct semantic roles/live regions for dynamic content, and reduced-motion support.</li><li>Validates both light and dark palettes against WCAG AA contrast ratios as part of the token pipeline, not by eyeballing.</li><li>Insists manual testing with real assistive tech (VoiceOver/TalkBack) on critical flows is a required gate, not something automated linting alone can substitute for.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Theming:</strong> a token layer (colors, spacing, typography) defined per theme (light/dark, optionally per-tenant), exposed through a <code>ThemeProvider</code>/context with a <code>setTheme</code>/<code>toggleTheme</code> API; default to <code>useColorScheme()</code> for the initial value but layer an explicit, persisted user override on top of it. All components consume colors exclusively via the theme hook — enforced by a lint rule banning raw hex/color literals in component styles — and both palettes are validated against WCAG AA contrast ratios (4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large text/UI) as part of the token-generation step. <strong>Accessibility beyond labels:</strong> use relative/scalable font sizing that respects the OS-level dynamic-type/font-scale setting instead of fixed px values that ignore it; give every interactive element correct <code>accessibilityRole</code>/<code>accessibilityLabel</code>/<code>accessibilityState</code>; route dynamically-updating content (toasts, live status) through <code>accessibilityLiveRegion</code>/<code>AccessibilityInfo.announceForAccessibility</code> so screen-reader users are notified without needing visual refocus; check <code>AccessibilityInfo.isReduceMotionEnabled()</code> and skip/simplify decorative animation for users who've requested reduced motion. <strong>Verification:</strong> automated a11y linting catches missing labels/roles/contrast mechanically, but the actual acceptance bar is a manual pass with VoiceOver (iOS) and TalkBack (Android) on the critical user flows — automated tooling can't catch broken focus order or a live region that never actually announces.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'Why is useColorScheme() alone not sufficient for theming?', a: "It only reflects the OS-level preference at a point in time. Users commonly want an explicit in-app override (force dark even if the OS is set to light, or vice versa) that persists across sessions — the theme context needs to layer a stored user preference on top of the system signal, not just mirror it." },
        { q: 'Automated accessibility audits pass, but a screen-reader user reports the app is unusable — why, and what do you check?', a: "Automated audits mostly catch missing labels, roles, and contrast — not reading order, logical grouping, or whether a multi-step flow is actually completable (focus getting trapped, or an updated live region never being announced). Those require actually navigating the critical flows with VoiceOver/TalkBack, which is why manual assistive-tech testing is a required gate rather than optional polish." }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-debug-scroll-jank', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: 'A production screen with a list of roughly 500 moderately complex rows is reported dropping frames while scrolling on real devices, though it tested fine earlier. Walk through how you would diagnose and fix it.',
    answer: {
      approach: `Ask what changed recently — is this an actual regression against a known-good build, or has it always been somewhat janky and is only now getting attention? Ask which devices reproduce it (low-end only, or across the board) and which list component and RN version/architecture are in use. Ask what profiling tooling is already available, since the diagnostic path depends entirely on being able to actually measure, not guess.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Reaches for profiling tools first — RN DevTools' JS profiler and a native profiler (Android GPU rendering profile / Instruments) — rather than guessing at a fix blind.</li><li>Explicitly separates <strong>JS-thread-bound</strong> jank (slow renders/handlers) from <strong>UI/native-thread-bound</strong> jank (view creation, layout, image decode), since the fixes are entirely different.</li><li>Checks the classic list-perf offenders: inline anonymous functions/objects as row props defeating memoization, unstable keys causing remounts instead of reordering, oversized images, and a non-recycling list component at this row count.</li><li>Verifies the fix with a re-measured profiler trace on the same real device that reproduced the regression — doesn't declare victory on vibes or a flagship-phone test.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Step 1 — measure, don't guess:</strong> profile the actual scroll interaction with RN DevTools' JS flame chart alongside a native profiler (Android GPU rendering profile / Perfetto, or Instruments' Time Profiler on iOS) to see whether dropped frames correlate with long JS-thread tasks or long native/UI-thread work — these have completely different fixes. <strong>Step 2 — if JS-thread-bound:</strong> check for unmemoized row components re-rendering unnecessarily — inline arrow functions or object literals passed as row props defeat <code>React.memo</code>'s reference-equality check on every render, so hoist/<code>useCallback</code>/<code>useMemo</code> them; check for an unstable <code>keyExtractor</code> forcing full remounts instead of reordering; check for per-item computation running inline in render that should be precomputed or memoized once. <strong>Step 3 — if UI/native-thread-bound:</strong> check image handling — oversized images requiring expensive per-row decode should be server-resized and run through an image component with an efficient built-in decode/cache pipeline; consider migrating off <code>FlatList</code> to FlashList v2 if the list isn't already using a recycling renderer, since FlatList mounts/unmounts views on scroll while FlashList recycles them — this matters a lot at ~500 rows of moderate complexity. <strong>Step 4:</strong> check for accidental synchronous JS-thread work inside scroll event handlers that should instead run via a Reanimated worklet or the native driver. <strong>Step 5 — verify:</strong> re-profile after each change in isolation rather than stacking several fixes at once, and confirm the frame-drop count/JS-frame-time actually improved on the same real low-end device that originally reproduced the issue, not the developer's own flagship phone.`,
      followups: [
        { q: "The JS profiler shows the JS thread mostly idle during the stutter — what does that redirect you toward?", a: "If the JS thread isn't the bottleneck, the constraint is native/UI-thread work — image decode cost, native view creation/layout (especially FlatList's mount/unmount-per-scroll behavior versus a recycling list), or a main-thread-blocking native module call. The next step is profiling on the native side (Android's GPU/rendering profiler, or Instruments' Time Profiler), not continuing to optimize JS render logic that isn't actually the constraint." },
        { q: 'How do you distinguish "this was always somewhat janky" from "this regressed recently"?', a: 'Bisect via release history against a fixed, repeatable profiling benchmark on the same physical device — re-run the identical profiled scroll interaction against a few recent release builds to find where the frame-time budget actually crossed the threshold, rather than trusting anecdotal "it feels new" reports, which are unreliable without a controlled before/after comparison.' }
      ]
    }
  });

  // ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  reg({
    id: 'rn-sd-debug-cold-start', track: 'rn', category: 'rn-system-design', difficulty: 'staff', type: 'scenario',
    prompt: "Product reports that the app's cold-start time has crept up across several releases and now noticeably lags competitors. Walk through how you would diagnose and reduce it.",
    answer: {
      approach: `Pin down exactly what "cold start" is being measured as — icon tap to first paint, to first interactive screen, or including the splash screen's own duration? Ask whether the regression is gradual creep or tied to a specific release, and whether it differs meaningfully between iOS and Android, since the two platforms often have different dominant bottlenecks. Ask whether bundle size or native-module count has grown noticeably, and what startup-measurement tooling already exists.`,
      seniorChecks: `<ul><li>Separates native process/bootstrap time from JS bundle load/parse/execute time from app-level time-to-interactive (first meaningful, data-driven paint) — treats these as different budgets with different fixes.</li><li>Checks whether Hermes bytecode precompilation is genuinely active for the release build, rather than assuming it silently still is.</li><li>Checks native-module footprint and whether hot-path modules are lazily instantiated (TurboModules) versus eagerly constructed at boot (legacy NativeModules) — a concrete, measurable startup-cost lever.</li><li>Checks whether the splash screen duration is masking real underlying slowness rather than the team fixing the actual time-to-interactive.</li><li>Insists on real measurement tooling (native startup tracing) rather than stopwatch-and-guess, and re-measures on the same device profile across releases to actually bisect the regression.</li></ul>`,
      walkthrough: `<strong>Step 1 — baseline with real tooling:</strong> split the measurement by phase — native process start → JS engine init → JS bundle load/parse/execute → first React render → time-to-interactive — using Android's <code>am start -W</code>/Perfetto trace or iOS's Instruments "App Launch" template, plus any RN-side startup timestamp markers already instrumented. <strong>Step 2 — confirm build config hasn't regressed:</strong> verify Hermes bytecode precompilation is actually active for the release build (a build misconfiguration silently falling back to interpreting raw JS is a classic, easy-to-miss regression) and confirm the app is running the bridgeless/New Architecture startup path rather than a heavier legacy bridge bootstrap — this comparison only matters for apps not yet on RN 0.82+, since 0.82 removed the legacy bridge and made New Architecture mandatory, leaving no legacy path to compare against on newer versions. <strong>Step 3 — audit native-module footprint:</strong> a native-module count that's grown release over release, especially if instantiated eagerly (legacy NativeModules construct every registered module at boot regardless of use), directly adds startup cost; migrating hot-path modules to lazy TurboModule instantiation is a concrete, measurable lever. <strong>Step 4 — audit JS bundle growth:</strong> track bundle size trend release-over-release — a bloated bundle takes longer to parse/execute even as precompiled bytecode — and look for eagerly-imported, rarely-used screens/libraries that should instead be lazily loaded/route-split out of the initial bundle. <strong>Step 5 — audit time-to-interactive specifically:</strong> a fast bundle load can still be masked by first-screen data fetches blocking the first useful render; move non-critical fetches behind the first paint (render a skeleton or cached data first, fetch-then-hydrate) instead of blocking on network before rendering anything. <strong>Step 6 — check the splash screen isn't a band-aid:</strong> extending splash duration hides slowness rather than fixing it — the metric that matters is genuine time-to-interactive, not time until the splash disappears.`,
      followups: [
        { q: 'The team suspects "it\'s just more native modules now" — how do you confirm or rule that out with data?', a: "Compare native-module construction time specifically across an older and current release build using native startup tracing (Perfetto/Instruments), isolating the segment spent in eager module instantiation during boot. If that segment grew proportionally to the overall regression, it's confirmed, and the fix is auditing which of those modules can move from eager legacy NativeModules registration to lazy TurboModule instantiation." },
        { q: 'Profiling shows JS bundle parse/execute time is the dominant regressed segment — what are the concrete levers?', a: "Verify Hermes bytecode precompilation hasn't silently regressed in the build config (an easy-to-miss misconfiguration), check bundle size growth over recent releases and split rarely-used screens/heavy libraries out of the initial bundle via lazy-loaded routes instead of one monolithic entry bundle, and check for accidentally duplicated dependencies (multiple versions of a large library bundled side by side) inflating parse cost." }
      ]
    }
  });

})();
